<section>
  <div class="professional-callout">
    <p><strong>Professionally, I work in identity security.</strong> That career — fifteen years across enterprise, federal, and critical-infrastructure environments — lives at <a href="https://www.ronniebailey.cloud" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ronniebailey.cloud</a>. This site is everything else.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="intro">
    <p>My interest in language began independently in 2008 while I was still in high school. What started as personal study gradually expanded into formal education, public service, and a broader interest in the institutions, history, and cultures that shape international engagement.</p>
    <p>This archive follows that progression — not as a résumé, but as a record of study, civic participation, and the experiences that continue to inform my professional perspective.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="timeline">
  <div class="sec-head">
    <h2>Studies &amp; Engagement <span class="fr-title">Études et engagement</span></h2>
    <p class="sec-note">A chronological record of formal study, language development, cultural exchange, public service, and civic engagement.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="timeline">
    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">Nov 2023 – Dec 2023<span class="where">U.S. Institute of Diplomacy and Human Rights · Washington, D.C.</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>Human Rights Education Training</h3>
        <p class="role">Human rights, diplomacy, advocacy</p>
        <p>Completed professional training in diplomacy and human-rights principles, with a focus on how international institutions frame advocacy and protection.</p>
        <div class="ref-links">
          <a href="archive/usidhr/certificate.pdf" target="_blank">Certificate</a>
          <a href="archive/usidhr/program-overview.pdf" target="_blank">Program overview</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">Sep 2017 – Apr 2018<span class="where">Architect of the Capitol · Washington, D.C.</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>Visitor Assistant · GS-5</h3>
        <p class="role">Public service, visitor engagement, historical interpretation</p>
        <p>Served in a public-facing role at a major U.S. civic institution, where historical interpretation became part of daily public service.</p>
        <div class="ref-links">
          <a href="archive/aoc/appointment.pdf" target="_blank">Appointment</a>
          <a href="archive/aoc/photographs.html" target="_blank">Photographs</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">Sep 2013 – Feb 2016<span class="where">Clark College Cercle Français · Vancouver, Washington</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>Vice President, Cercle Français</h3>
        <p class="role">Clark College</p>
        <p>Supported campus programming that connected French language study with cultural exchange and community engagement.</p>
        <div class="ref-links">
          <a href="archive/french-club/leadership-record.pdf" target="_blank">Leadership record</a>
          <a href="archive/french-club/photos.html" target="_blank">Photographs</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">Jan 2014 – Oct 2015<span class="where">Alliance Française de Portland · Portland, Oregon</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>French Language Study</h3>
        <p class="role">Courses 101 and 103</p>
        <p>Completed French language group courses 101 and 103 through a cultural institution dedicated to Francophone language and exchange.</p>
        <div class="ref-links">
          <a href="archive/alliance-francaise/attendance-letter.pdf" target="_blank">Attendance letter</a>
          <a href="archive/alliance-francaise/study-materials.html" target="_blank">Study materials</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">Jul 2013 – Aug 2016<span class="where">Clark College · Vancouver, Washington</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>International Relations &amp; Affairs</h3>
        <p class="role">Associate of Arts coursework</p>
        <p>Studied international relations within a broader academic path that connected public communication, literature, public speaking, global affairs, and policy.</p>
        <div class="ref-links">
          <a href="archive/clark-college/transcript.pdf" target="_blank">Transcript</a>
          <a href="archive/clark-college/degree.pdf" target="_blank">Degree record</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">Jan 2013<span class="where">Lang-8, Inc. · Shibuya-ku, Tokyo, Japan · Remote</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>Language Interpreter &amp; Cultural Liaison</h3>
        <p class="role">French-English interpretation, language exchange</p>
        <p>Supported a Tokyo-headquartered language exchange platform through French-English interpretation, translation support, and coaching within a global learning community.</p>
        <div class="ref-links">
          <a href="archive/lang8/profile.pdf" target="_blank">Platform profile</a>
          <a href="archive/lang8/translation-samples.pdf" target="_blank">Translation samples</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">2008 – 2013<span class="where">Independent Study · Richmond, Virginia</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>Independent Language Study</h3>
        <p class="role">French language exploration</p>
        <p>Began independent French study through self-directed coursework, language audio programs, online communities, and international correspondence. That early interest later expanded into university coursework, Alliance Française instruction, language exchange, and a broader interest in cultural diplomacy.</p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="entry">
      <div class="when">2008<span class="where">All On The Line · Richmond, Virginia · On-site</span></div>
      <div>
        <h3>Political Canvasser</h3>
